{"type":"assistant","message":{"model":"claude-sonnet-4-6","id":"msg_01LNDoKhALasmGWujAu3sn9r","type":"message","role":"assistant","content":[{"type":"thinking","thinking":"Now I have a clear picture. This is a TOP-level decompose task (Complexity: —). I need to:\n\n1. Identify the top-level components of the platform (networked monolith)\n2. Determine which are atomic vs composite\n3. Write documentation files\n4. Emit the `<response>` XML block\n\nLet me think through the component breakdown:\n\n**Platform Structure:**\n- Single binary: `cmd/platform/main.go`\n- Two HTTP listeners: metrics (8081) and IAM (8082)\n\n**Top-level components:**\n\n1. **metrics** (composite or atomic?) — The metrics service handles POST /events and GET /events. \n\nIt needs a store and handlers, which is straightforward enough that I'll classify it as atomic. The in-memory event storage and the two HTTP endpoints are simple enough to treat as a single cohesive unit.\n\n2. **iam** (composite) — IAM is \"internally composed of two logical components: (\n\na) user authentication and lifecycle, and (b) authorisation/RBAC.\" This is explicitly composite, so I'll break it into sub-components: lifecycle handles user auth and management endpoints, authz-rbac handles role and permission checking, and then I'll need an integrate-iam component to wire them together.\n\n3. **integrate-platform** (atomic) — The top-level integration step that brings metrics and IAM into the platform binary.\n\nFor metrics, the in-memory event storage with POST and GET handlers is small enough to stay atomic.\n\nSo my top-level structure is: metrics (atomic), iam (composite), and integrate-platform (atomic), with both metrics and iam living under `internal/`.\n\nSince `internal` is a Go convention directory, I skip the composite-level documentation and let each child component write its own README when decomposed.\n\nNow I need to figure out the description fields carefully. iam into the platform's main entry point, wiring both the metrics listener on 8081 and IAM listener on 8082, then writing end-to-end acceptance tests that exercise all 12 endpoints across both services. Since `internal/` is a Go convention directory, I'll skip the README and theory-of-operation docs — those will be written by each composite child if they're decomposed later. Now I need to flesh out the full API descriptions for each component, starting with the complete contract for metrics including all endpoint details from the acceptance spec. Now I need to wire both the metrics and IAM services into a single platform binary, starting the metrics listener on port 8081 and the IAM listener on port 8082 in separate goroutines. The acceptance tests should cover all 12 endpoints across both services—the metrics endpoints for event creation and retrieval, plus the IAM endpoints for user management, authentication, and authorization operations. I'm checking the exception rule for Go convention directories — since `internal/` is a standard Go pattern, I should skip writing docs for it and let each child component document itself later. The metrics service is small and atomic with just two endpoints, while the IAM service is clearly composite with ten endpoints spanning user lifecycle, auth, and RBAC concerns. I need to make sure I'm using the correct package path as the source directory for metrics.\n\nNow I'm ready to compose the response — I'll skip the parent directory docs since it's a Go convention, write a detailed contract for metrics with all endpoint specifics, keep the IAM description brief since it's composite, and provide full wiring and acceptance criteria for the integrate-platform component.","signature":""}],"stop_reason":null,"stop_sequence":null,"stop_details":null,"usage":{"input_tokens":1,"cache_creation_input_tokens":1025,"cache_read_input_tokens":20394,"cache_creation":{"ephemeral_5m_input_tokens":0,"ephemeral_1h_input_tokens":1025},"output_tokens":20,"service_tier":"standard","inference_g